  fiber: 6 g
  sodium: 970 mg
time required: 35 minutes
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @Carrots{9%ounce} on a diagonal into 1⁄2-inch-thick pieces. Peel and mince or grate @Garlic{2%clove}. Halve, peel, and mince @Shallot{1}. Roughly chop @Parsley{¼%ounce}.

Toss carrots on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @Cooking Oil{}, @Salt{}, and @Pepper{}. Roast on top rack until tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} in a #small pot{} (medium pot for 4 servings) over medium-high heat. Add @Israeli Couscous{2.5%ounce}, half the garlic, 1 TBSP shallot (2 TBSP for 4), and a pinch of @Salt{pinch} and @Pepper{pinch}. Cook, stirring, until garlic is fragrant and couscous is lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add half the @Beef Stock Concentrate{2}. Add 3⁄4 cup @water{¾%cup} (1 1/2 cups for 4). Bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer and cover. Cook until couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Pat @Salmon{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with @Italian Seasoning{1%tablespoon} (2 tsp for 4 servings), a big pinch of @Salt{pinch}, and @Pepper{}. (Be sure to measure the Italian Seasoning—we sent more!)

Heat a large drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add salmon and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes} per side. (TIP: Reduce heat if salmon is browning too quickly.) Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest. Wipe out pan and allow to cool for ~{1%minute}.

> Swap in chicken for pork, or cook salmon (skin sides down) until skin is crisp, then flip and cook until cooked through, 1-2 minutes more.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} in same pan over medium heat. Add remaining shallot and remaining garlic; cook, stirring, until softened and lightly browned, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @Tomato Paste{1}, remaining stock concentrate, and @water{½%cup} (3⁄4 cup for 4 servings). Bring to a simmer and cook until reduced, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove from heat and stir in @Sour Cream{3%tablespoon}. Season generously with @Pepper{}. TIP: If sauce is too thick, add water 1 tsp at a time until sauce reaches desired consistency.

Fluff couscous gently with a #fork{}; stir in @Butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings).

Thinly slice salmon crosswise.

> Thinly slice chicken crosswise (skip slicing salmon!).

Divide couscous and carrots between #plates{}. Fan salmon over couscous. Spoon sauce over salmon. Sprinkle with parsley and serve.

> Salmon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.